        Cha-Cha-Chart Review 16/08/24

        Excuse the title, but given how dominant artists whose names start with these three letters are at this point, I might as well get in the spirit. After all, if they can all jump on the bandwagon and make a trend seem incredibly outdated, why can't I?

        Yes folks, it's that time of the week again, where I look over the stale situation of the UK music scene, realise that there's no point marking the days for how long Noah Kahan will spend in the Top 40, and treat every new hit as if they're either the second coming of Nelly Furtado, Simply Red, or Gary Glitter. Depending on how I feel about the songs they release, of course. Having said that though, I haven't actually heard any hits from the latter, which is probably for the best. I mean, could you imagine wh-

        INSERT JOKE ABOUT THAT FRAUD HERE

        Enough about has-beens, it's time for what is in right now. And, to the delight of Radio 1 producers, Roni Size, and every British dance oficionado the human race can track down, there's another new chart-topper to decipher. Charli XCX and Billie Eilish prove just how far a ravenous fanbase can actually take you as they drop to 4, and with Chappell Roan stubbornly refusing to take the glory, Sabrina Carpenter catapulting to ACR, and the other so-called "contenders" limping to the finish, it's about time we recognised one of UK music's great institutions. Ever since double A-side Love's Theme/Wise Up popped up at 76 in April 2005, Saul Milton and Will Kennard have gone from challenging fellow unworthy beat bashers like J Majik and Wickaman (who?) to getting to hang out with Rihanna and make barn-storming classics like Let You Go, Blind Faith, and Lost & Not Found. That's what I would've said 10 years ago if they kept up this string of success. Because they didn't. Follow-up singles with the likes of Tom Grennan and George The Poet flopped dramatically, their albums appeared and disappeared with immediate effect, and when Mixed Emotions fell apart at No.44 in 2022, you could be forgiven for thinking they'd vanish off the face of the Earth.

        But in a funny twist of events, some stuff happened last year that caught everyone offguard. Not only did hanging out with Becky Hill give her a massive hit that didn't STINK, but their own single Baddadan decided to parachute it's way into the Top 5 out of nowhere to the sound of extremely loud beats 'n' pieces that Bru-C would chew his left earlobe off for. Since then, follow-up effort Liquor & Cigarettes went Top 20, but it's clear that the future singles were the ones to look forward to. The ones to try and establish themselves again. The ones that can finally get them to be noticed in the eyes of the notoriously fickle British public, who are too obsessed with Teddy Swims and Will Young (be grateful his album's tanked today) to care about appreciating brilliant music.

        Gonna assume they've done it then.

        BACKBONE features the gloriously rude and Bri'ish tones of everyone's favourite UK rapper Stormzy, who probably needs the help given the disappointing result of his last album, and if you took one listen at the songs on 2 RUFF Vol. 1 then you'll know it off by heart. One long threatening speech by Mr. Omari, synthesizers squeezing through your eardrums that could make Pendulum jealous, and a sense that you can feel the public's affections shifting again. And boy, have they shifted. Straight in at No.1 today, this is easily the biggest hit that Chase & Status will ever have, and the fact it's debuted at the top of the biased Capital chart as well means that something pretty special is happening here. Even if it isn't the best thing they've done (the aforementioned Blind Faith takes it for me).

        Typical, eh? You wait all year for a British chart-topper and then two come at once.

        Naturally, the rest of the chart has cowered in fear at this, because nothing has happened. So I might as well give the climbers some love, except the song returning to the Top 10 is the song of the summer (it isn't, not by a LONG way) from JADE. Blame everyone gagging on a slower remix for this shooting up 8 places OK? Her streams are off a cliff, so Mixers out there have to accept your fatal case of double standards. Also rising a lot is Hanumankind, Big Dawgs narrowly missing the Top 20 thanks to me not caring for it, and get ready for Sonny Fodera Round 2 folks, 'cos Somedays has shot to 19 and there's nothing you can do about it. Sowwee.

        Also riding high in the 20 are *NSYNC, who may have dropped one with their Deadpool & Wolverine pop-up ad, but can now be joined by Like A Prayer by Madonna, who I completely didn't notice re-enter at 95 last week, so her rocket up to 27 today is entirely down to the iTunes folk buying multiple releases and making my life misery. Her 66th birthday today may also have something to do with the song's ACR reset. Predictably. The only other NEW entry meanwhile is the 3rd hit for Gracie Abrams, who may or may not be Taylor Swift's father's brother's sister's cousin's nephew's uncle-in-law's auntie. That depends on who you ask of course. Either way, I Love You, I'm Sorry has crept to 38 after missing the best-sellers last week, and I can confirm that it's really hard to tell it apart from her other hits. It's not my fault, OK? If she stopped making folklore and evermore off-cuts I'd maybe respect her more.

        Oh, and the lovely beabadoobee has bagged her first No.1 album today, and if you are invested, I suggest you hear opener and lead single Take A Bite, and then promptly abandon it because nothing she'll ever make can possibly top that majestic piece of music. Except maybe 10:36, but clearly my opinions aren't important.

        Elsewhere and Gigi Perez has risen to 43, so prepare your folk machines and buckle up, Lost Frequencies (I'm not letting Tom Odell witness this travesty) and Alex Warren have also shot up the listings, Asake hires Travis Scott for a song on his new album and it works, Shawn Mendes is back and he's a fraud, Clean Bandit really need to stop at this point, Drake is cancelled but you knew that already, Katy Perry should just give up by now, and PAWSA makes a 2nd appearance after forcing Nate Dogg to guest star on PICK UP THE PHONE from beyond the grave. Unsurprisingly, none of these are very memorable.

        Out today though is a duet between Lady Gaga and Bruno Mars, so expect that to run riot along with a bunch of stuff from Post Malone's new (country) album, meanwhile The Script, Foster The People and Falling In Reverse have new LPs, and Hozier, Peggy Gou, Halsey, LISA/ROSALA and The Blessed Madonna/Kylie can also be found fighting for relevance. So expect more ramblings from me mext week. Until then, chumps.
